{"questionId":"9083135","questionHtml":"<p>Show that the apparent brightness&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>∝</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>A</mi><msup><mi>T</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi></math> is the distance of the object from Earth, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math> is the surface temperature of the object and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math> is the surface area of the object.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>substitution of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>σ</mi><mi>A</mi><msup><mi>T</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;into&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>πd</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;giving&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>σ</mi><mi>A</mi><msup><mi>T</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>πd</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><span class=\"fontstyle0\">Removal of constants <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>σ</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></math>&nbsp;is optional</span></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9083135","referenceCode":"20N.2.SL.TZ0.a","subjectId":"59-dp-physics-first-assessment-2025","title":"Show that the apparent brightness b∝AT4d2, where d is the distance of the object from Earth, T is the surface temperature of the object and A is the surface area of the object.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["E. Nuclear and quantum physics","E.5 Fusion and stars"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}